<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-11T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-11T15:00:00-05:00" n="1044" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1044">
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-11T15:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 11, 1912—3 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your request for instructions as to informing Americans they should leave
                            Chihuahua received in undated telegram.<note n="1" xml:id="d1044fn1">See
                                telegram received April 10.</note> Department must depend upon you
                            and Americans themselves in the first instance to decide whether or not
                            local conditions warrant their departure for a place of safety; but it
                            feels that you may make quiet suggestions to Americans to leave as soon
                            and as unobtrusively as possible in case you still believe it
                            necessary.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>